A mid-term report by a working group set up by the Republican Chairman of the House Defense Forces Committee, the Intelligence Committee, and the Defence Budget Subcommittee found “widespread dissatisfaction” among headquarters intelligence analysts, who said the superiors were judging their assessments of American efforts to defeat ISIS.
Headquarters, known as Centcomin, is a military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, which oversees U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
“Intelligence outputs approved by senior Centcom executives typically gave a more positive picture of U.S. counter-terrorism efforts than the facts on the ground justified. They were consistently more positive than the analysis produced by other agents in the intelligence community,” the report said in a press release.
“Centcom’s events are unacceptable — our fighters in the war suffer when bad analyses are presented to high-ranking decision makers,” spokesman Ken Calvert, a California Republican, said in a statement.
The failures of Centcom’s management reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report describes in detail the ongoing problems in headquarters descriptions and analyses of the US efforts to train Iraqi troops in 2014 and 2015.
While it does not provide clear evidence that senior Obama administration officials have ordered reports to be tampered with, it describes analysts feeling as if Centcom leaders had put pressure on them to portray the threat posed by the Islamic state, ISIS, in a more positive light.
“Throughout the first half of 2015, many of the headquarters’ press releases, statements, and testimonies to Congress were significantly more positive than the events themselves,” the report said.
For example, a Centcom official publicly stated that a major attack to recapture Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, the second largest city in Iraq, is still under Islamic State control.
"After months of investigation, this is very clear," spokesman Mike Pompeo, a Republican in Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, senior intelligence chiefs at the U.S. military headquarters manipulated the headquarters’ intelligence output to minimize the ISIS threat in Iraq.
The team was created by Republicans when they heard that analysts had raised concerns that intelligence about the Islamic state was being manipulated.
The report, published on Thursday, will be followed by more extensive results while the investigation is ongoing.
The Department of Defense's Chief Inspector has launched an extra, ongoing investigation into Centcom's intelligence.
Democratic members of the House Intelligence Committee released their own findings on Thursday, consistent with some of the Republican working group’s conclusions.
"Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an unnecessarily isolated process of intelligence assessment by the ISIS and Iraqi security forces," said Adam B. Schiff, the committee's chief Democrat.
According to Schiff, this process “prolonged the publication of inquiries,” worsened the mood among analysts, and “given not enough room for divergent perspectives.”
Schiff and the Democrats said they found no evidence that the White House was trying to pressure Centcom analysts to reconcile their conclusions with “pre-set or political narrative.”
On Tuesday, The Daily Beast reported on the preliminary results of the congressional investigation.
Last August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon’s Chief Inspector had opened an investigation following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Commander-in-Chief Patrick Evans, a spokesman for the Pentagon, said in a statement that the Department of Defense will not comment on the Congressional report as long as the Inspector General’s investigation is ongoing.
But he said that “experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these essential national security issues.”
The investigation has other repercussions than just the question of whether US-led bombings in Iraq and Syria are successful (as a growing number of defense officials now claim).
Last year’s accusations questioned how much President Obama can count on the headquarters to provide honest estimates of military action in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis locations.
The criticism of Islamic State intelligence reflects a controversy more than a decade ago when Centcom’s intelligence analyst, Gregory Hooker, wrote a research article that said that despite the objections of several analysts, the administration of President George W. Bush supported a small army in Iraq and spent very little time contemplating the consequences of the 2003 attack.
Hooker also played a key role in the rebellion against Islamic State intelligence.
Last year, the Hooker group concluded that, despite public statements to the contrary, air strikes against Islamic state-controlled refineries had not significantly weakened the economy of the terrorist group because it had built temporary refineries to sell oil through the black market.
The Times reported in September that this discovery was not reported outside headquarters.
Centcom's then commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after many legislators regarded his testimony to the Senate as an over-positive assessment of the war.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced by General Joseph L. Votel.
