Trampoline peace in the middle of the Olympics
Wherever you are, whatever the time, the Olympics are on.
The events in Rio de Janeiro seem to be a constant and inevitable, a fierce message of competition and effort.
It’s as if the Olympic torch itself is a flaming stick that is transmitted from the archer to the swimmer and from the gymnast to the triathlete.
It’s impossible to turn on a TV, read a newspaper, or listen to a neighbor’s conversation in a café queue without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the hatred between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, the first-time Olympic champion and future heartbreaker with a smile, could well be one of those well-known names that are presented at prime time, supported by sponsorship agreements and good-natured TV commercials - if he were a swimmer, a gymnast or even a swordsman.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is competing for Olympic gold in a trampoline.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate all species equally.
Farther from the center, partly in the shade, are those species that are not generally accepted by everyone: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We'll always have a breaststroke, long live it.
But if I may make a moderate number of my special favourites, I would like to draw attention to the subdued charm of the trampoline.
Although the trampoline has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it made its first appearance at the Sydney Games, there has been so little notice of its presence in between over the past 16 years that many of the people I interviewed did not realize at all that it was an Olympic sport.
This may be regional ignorance.
Although the United States has sent athletes to compete in the sport, it has never won a medal in it, and its athlete did not progress to the finals until 2012.
Chinese and Russians usually share medals for men, Chinese and Canadian women.
This year, Chinese Dong Dong and Canadian Rosie McLennan will defend their London gold medals.
The trampoline, however, has a certain underdog charm, partly because it sounds more suitable for clown school than for the Olympics.
In this I have to admit that I am not an expert, I am just a fan of flightlessness.
The sport has potential for amusing, as can be seen from the endless swings of cartoons, but it also has the sweetness of gymnastics and swimming, two species that basically combine in it.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish word el trampol<0xC3><0xAD>n, which means "springboard".
The champions jumped up to almost 30 feet in a giant trampoline, and they have to perform twisting sequences of movements (turns, folds and folds) and finally land on their feet.
According to the official Olympic program, they are assessed on the basis of execution, difficulty and "flight time".
In Rio, 32 athletes from 17 countries compete, 16 men and 16 women.
The most common direction of the Olympics is straight ahead.
Those looking for a medal must go further, faster, up and over - sometimes to the finish line, sometimes back and forth around the pitch.
They hunt not only for the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in television news coverage, for another ridiculous frontier: a world record or an Olympic record.
This determined pursuit is noble, admirable and even fanatical - and can even bring the viewer to tears.
But that’s also why watching the games can be a bit exhausting.
The trampoline offers a rest from this.
Trampoline's up.
The goal is not to move forward.
The competitor rises to a new rise, appearing weightless as an astronaut, going up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
Of course, this is not without competition or difficulty, but during the program there is no furious rush towards the end, no leaps into the distance, only a dreamlike, smooth interruption of time and gravity.
It is as close to Zen space as can be achieved at the Olympics.
The women’s qualifiers and then the final will be held on Friday afternoon at 1 pm (ET), the men’s qualifiers will also be held on Saturday at 1 pm.
NBC will broadcast the finals as part of their afternoon schedule starting at 2 p.m. on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic hustle and bustle, they offer a quiet, charming moment that most likely will not be noticed in the general chaos.
And if consciousness is only attained by offering male athletes to stare at and objectify (as recently suggested by U.S. male gymnasts, according to The Wall Street Journal), Dooley is just waiting for his sighing new fan base.
"Generation Protests" in Ethiopia, a long-standing ally of the United States
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters calling for political change in Ethiopia have faced violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters have been shot dead in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia breaking?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a strong ally of the West, whose economy is growing rapidly.
In recent months, however, protests against the government have shaken the country as they spread to more and more areas.
Last week alone, thousands of people rushed into the streets demanding a fundamental political change.
Human rights groups said the government's response was ruthless.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Widespread video footage of demonstrations, believed to be at the end of last year or the beginning of this year, shows how security officials beat young people with sticks while forcing them to stand with their hands against the wall.
The U.N. Human Rights Authority is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"Holding this country together has always been difficult, and it will be even more difficult in the future," said Rashid Abdi, project manager for the International Crisis Group in the Horn of Africa.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and the West appreciates its stability.
American military and intelligence services work closely with the Ethiopians in the fight against terrorist threats in the region, particularly in Somalia, and hardly any African country receives so much Western aid.
Ethiopia’s economy has grown at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved enormously, and the capital city of Addis Ababa even has a new commuter train.
The streets of the city are typically quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia has not been a model of democracy, human rights organisations have been constantly talking about repression by the government, the opposition in the country has been limited and dissidents have been effectively silenced.
Many have been deported, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the desert.
But this may be changing.
"If you suppress people and they have no choice but to protest, this is what will happen," Seyoum Teshome, a university teacher from Central Ethiopia, said.
All the young people are demonstrating.
One generation is demonstrating.
Complaints are diverse and cover everything from land use to the stranglehold of coalition power.
After the much-criticised elections last year, the ruling party and its allies received the last seat held by the opposition and now holds all the seats in parliament.
At the same time, tensions on the border with Eritrea are increasing, and the battle along this tense and controversial border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, may try to exploit the turmoil and re-arm themselves.
Numerous factors explain why, after years of turmoil beneath the surface, bitter emotions are now exploding.
The first seems seemingly harmless: smartphones.
It is only in the last few years that a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate through social media, as cheaper smartphones have become more common and the internet service has improved.
Even if the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often does, especially during demonstrations, many people can still communicate through location-hiding network proxy servers.
Many young Ethiopians said that this was how they gathered for the demonstrations.
Secondly, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia, the Oromo and the Amharic, get along better.
The Oromo and the Amharic are not natural allies.
For a very long time, the Amharic, who came mainly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, prospered in politics and business, exploiting the Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and who live in the lowlands.
But this is also changing.
"We're on our way to organizing under one umbrella," Oromo Director Mulatu Gemechu said.
The biggest protests have been in the Amharic and Oromo regions.
Many Amharic and Oromo think that Ethiopia is unfairly ruled by members of the Tigre people, who cover about 6% of the population and control the armed forces, intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, was Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years until he died of a secret illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around the corners.
Analysts say he was particularly qualified to detect early signs of dissatisfaction and to use secret ambassadors to make opponents harmless.
“The current administration does not have such a basic instinct,” said conflict analyst Abdi.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalegn, was picked relatively unknown to fill Meles' boots.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigre region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is from the south.
Analysts say the security services controlled by the tigers don't trust him.
Many fear that this may lead to increased bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia was in such a state of turmoil was in 2005, when thousands protested about elections that, according to analysts, appeared to be first rigged and then looted by the government.
In the ensuing strike, many demonstrators died, albeit fewer than in recent months, and that period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopian leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as the new commuter train, and for their remarkable progress in the fight against poverty.
But clearly this has not stopped the intensification of contempt for the Ethiopian government within the country.
And now it's starting to take on a dangerous, ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked businesses owned by tigers, and anti-tiger hatred is becoming more and more common on social media.
Analysts say the protests are putting the United States and other Western allies in a clumsy position.
The American government has used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights to neighbouring Somalia, even though it recently said it had closed this base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it also does not want its already unstable allies to collapse.
"This," said Abdi, "is a real balancing act."
