Strikes against the oilfield service company Wood Group have been randomly organised on drilling platforms in the North Sea run by Royal Dutch Shell.
“Wood Group and Unite and RMT can confirm that we have agreed to restart the process of resolving the current dispute,” the joint statement said.
Over the next few weeks, we will hold several full-day meetings, starting early next week, so that we can take a fresh look at the problems.
Trade unions say their recent industrial action, which they say will be the first in more than 25 years, was a protest against potential pay cuts of up to 30%.
This year, Wood Group cut North Sea contractors’ commissions by about 9% due to negative market pressure.
The reduction in the company’s remuneration follows a 10% decrease in the number of contractors in its countries in 2014.
The company said further cuts would give the company the necessary room for manoeuvre to cope with the market downturn.
Shell, on the other hand, has cut thousands of people's payroll and announced plans to leave oil and gas operations in up to 10 countries as the company lightens its operations as a result of its giant merger with the British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure from lower crude oil prices, and this economic situation is exacerbated by Britain’s June decision to leave the European Union.
Scottish MEP Dave Anderson met with federal leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest labour disputes of the generation in the North Sea.
He said that the North Sea is essential to the region's economy.
“We need an economy that works for many, not just a few, both in the North Sea and across the country,” he said in a statement.
