Kepler measures the rotational speed of stars in the Pleiadian cluster
The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers gather the most complete list of the star rotation speeds of the Pleiadian star cluster.
The new data will help astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at varying speeds and how rotational times are related to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will now learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system," said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at the Pasadena Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at Caltech.
The Pleiadian star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born about 125 million years ago, and are now reaching adulthood.
They are now at their highest level.
At their peak rotational speed, these mature stars throw large amounts of star wind.
When these winds pass through the magnetic fields of the stars, they brake the stars.
As the star ages, its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by tracking the appearance of recognisable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest list of star rotation speeds suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, the bigger ones making pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades 'ballet,' we see that slow spinners tend to be more massive, while the fastest spinners tend to be very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiadian star cluster is so close, it is an ideal cosmic laboratory for estimating the properties of stars at rotational speeds.
"The Pleiadian star cluster provides an anchor for stellar rotation in theoretical models that encompass both directions, younger and older," Rebull said.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when and why stars slow down their rotational speed and so to speak hang their ‘dance shoes’ on the nail.
Rebull and his colleagues described their latest analysis of Pleiadian rotational velocities in three articles to be published shortly in the Astronomical Journal.
